(1, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Introduction to chemistry.', '60978988-3479-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Hello and welcome! \r\n\r\nIn this lesson we\\\'ll be looking at an in-depth Introduction\r\nto chemistry.\r\n\r\nAt the end of the lesson you should be able to:\r\n\r\nA. Define what chemistry is\r\n\r\nB. Explain why we study chemistry\r\n\r\nC. Explain the scientific methods\r\n\r\nD. And describe the applications of chemistry in our day to\r\nday life.\r\n\r\nDid you know that chemistry is as old as man himself? Chemistry\r\nbegan the moment our ancestors became human.\r\n\r\nPeople associate certain images with chemistry, images like\r\na man/woman in a lab coat, like mine here (smiles), the periodic table, vials\r\nof chemicals etcetera.\r\n\r\nChemistry is a science, it is one of the physical sciences\r\nthat brings with it an explanation to the world in which we live. It is\r\ninvolved in everything we do such as cooking, burning firewood, cleaning, rusting\r\nnails, lighting a match etc. Every material we see around us is made up of\r\nmatter, our bodies inclusive.\r\n\r\nIn chemistry one thing we\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'ll talk about frequently is chemicals.\r\nNow, chemicals simply put are all forms of matter whether they be natural or artificial.\r\n\r\nSo what is chemistry? Chemistry is a branch of science that\r\ndeals with the study of matter it\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s structure composition properties and the\r\nchanges it undergoes. Matter is anything that has mass and occupies space. Do\r\nyou have mass? Do you occupy space? Then you are matter.\r\n\r\nWe study Chemistry to understand the behavior of matter under\r\ndifferent conditions. The study of chemistry helps us to understand our world. It\r\nalso enables us to acquire scientific skills, which in turn helps us to become problem\r\nsolvers. Wouldn\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'t you like to be a problem solver? Chemistry can help you\r\nbecome a critical thinker which will improve your problem solving skills. So, do\r\nyou see now that studying chemistry is fun! because in it we explore our world,\r\nwe delve into understanding the world and principles of how it operates. Never consider\r\nchemistry to be just another boring science course, because it is of paramount importance\r\nto our lives and our world today!\r\n\r\nThe branches of chemistry, include:\r\n\r\nAnalytical chemistry\r\n\r\nPhysical chemistry\r\n\r\nOrganic chemistry\r\n\r\nInorganic chemistry\r\n\r\nBio-chemistry\r\n\r\nPharmaceutical chemistry\r\n\r\nEnvironmental chemistry\r\n\r\nPetroleum chemistry\r\n\r\nAstronomical chemistry etcetera.\r\n\r\nSo you see, chemistry has several career paths that one can follow.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe scientific method\r\n\r\nHave you ever wondered what happens to water when salt is\r\nadded to it? Do you think it freezes faster or not? You\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'re thinking like a\r\nscientist. \r\n\r\nChemistry alongside other fields of science has developed a\r\nmeans to make discoveries. This method is known as the scientific method.\r\nScientific method can be applied to everyday problems. It is a method of\r\ninvestigation, involving experimentation and observation to acquire new\r\nknowledge, to solve problems, and answer questions that are posed.\r\n\r\nThe Steps in the Scientific Method include:\r\n\r\nStep 1: Observations: scientists are very alert and inquisitive.\r\nTherefore, they observe and see certain patterns around us leading to a set of\r\nproblems which they try to solve. When you try to discover what happens to that\r\nsalt water solution, you\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'re being observant, just like a scientist!\r\n\r\nStep 2: Hypothesis: suggest a possible solution or explanation.\r\nA suggested solution is called a hypothesis. We have 2 kinds of hypothesis, the\r\nnull hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis. Take the salt water analogy for\r\ninstance, you put forth a hypothesis. The null hypothesis is that there will be\r\nno difference in how long it takes the water to freeze, whether or not it has salt\r\nadded to it. The alternative hypothesis is that there will be a significant\r\ndifference in freezing time between the two scenarios (with salt and or without\r\nsalt). \r\n\r\nStep 3: Experiment: test the hypothesis by making new\r\nobservations. You do this by carrying out experiments to test and record\r\nresults. Let\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s go back to our salt water analogy. Fill two similar containers\r\nwith the same amount of water at same temperatures, preferably room temperature.\r\nAdd a measured amount of salt to one of the containers. Place the two\r\ncontainers in a freezer. At regular intervals, open the freezer and observe the\r\nstatus of the water in each container. Continue until both have frozen\r\ncompletely. Write down the time it took for each container of water to reach a\r\nfully frozen state. This is known as the experiment and results stage.\r\n\r\nStep 4: Theory: this is an idea suggested that explains an experiment.\r\nIf the new observations support the hypothesis - whether the null or alternative\r\nhypothesis- you accept the hypothesis for further testing, this is because\r\nscientists are meticulous and try to eliminate errors. If the new observations\r\ndo not agree with your hypothesis, add the new observations to your observation\r\nlist and return to Step 3 and carry out the experiment again. A theory is\r\nusually testable, if it doesn\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'t explain the hypothesis it can be modified or discarded\r\nto form a new one.\r\n\r\nUses and applications of chemistry.\r\n\r\nChemistry has made great contributions to several fields all\r\nin the bid to improve our quality of life. These fields include:\r\n\r\nAgriculture: study of chemistry has led to improvement in\r\nfarming techniques to provide improved seedlings for the production of valuable,\r\nhealthy, highly disease-resistant crop for both human and animal consumption. Similarly\r\nimproved breeds of animals are produced through chemical technology. These new\r\ntechnology has replaced the crude and uncivilized way of farming. \r\n\r\nHousing: through chemical technologies houses are\r\nconstructed with cement blocks, burnt bricks enforced with iron rods,\r\ngalvanized corrugated roofing sheets having tiles and marble floors in order to\r\nmake living comfortable and protecting one from adverse effect of climate\r\nconditions. These new technology has replaced mud housing built with thatched\r\nroofs. \r\n\r\nClothing and Textile: a wide range of clothing materials\r\nhave been made available as a result of intensive chemical research. This has\r\nreplaced the old and crude way of cloth making with hands, to cloth making with\r\nsophisticated machines. \r\n\r\nWarfare: territories are protected from insurgents or\r\nenemies by the use of sophisticated weapons engineered through technology. Such\r\nweapons include guns, ballistic missiles, bombs, landmine, biological weapons\r\netc. These weapons have replaced crude weapons such as spears, clubs, catapults,\r\nknives and arrows. \r\n\r\nMedicine: through chemical technology drugs are synthesized\r\ninto sizable quantities to be consumed orally or injected to cure one ailment\r\nor the other. Through these improved medical facilities, the lifespan of humans\r\nare now prolonged mortality rate has reduced considerately hence leading to\r\noverpopulation of the human race. These technological Innovations replaced the\r\nuse of crude herbs and other medical practices.\r\n\r\nTransportation: in ancient times movement from one place to\r\nanother was basically on land and Water by means of Beast of Burden like; donkeys,\r\nhorses, camels etc as well as trekking and use of canoes, boats and water ways.\r\nToday the transportation industry has been revolutionized. One can travel now from\r\none end of the world to another within a matter of hours.\r\n\r\nNow, the day to day applications of chemistry consists of\r\ndaily activities such as:\r\n\r\nBurning a candle\r\n\r\nUse of batteries in devices\r\n\r\nCooking with firewood, kerosene and or gas\r\n\r\nUse of soap whether for washing or bathing\r\n\r\nBoiling and frying food in the kitchen.\r\n\r\nDemerits of chemistry. \r\n\r\nNow we all know everything with a plus side, also has a down\r\nside, and chemistry isn\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'t excluded. The disadvantages of chemistry are hazardous\r\nand have adverse effects on living and non living things. These include:\r\n\r\nCorrosion: this is the process of gradually destroying materials\r\n(usually a metal) by chemical and/or electrochemical reactions with their\r\nenvironment. These materials when exposed to the atmosphere and water rust,\r\nbringing about degradation. In order to prevent corrosion or rusting, these\r\nmaterials are either protected by coating or replaced all together, this leads\r\nto additional costs.\r\n\r\nPollution: the plastics you see around that litter the\r\nenvironment are not biodegradable, meaning they cannot be decomposed by\r\nbiological activities, this causes soil pollution. Petrochemical industries\r\ndump chemical wastes which causes water and soil pollution. The exhaust of\r\nvehicles emit harmful gases like carbon monoxide, causing air pollution.\r\n\r\nLet\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s do a quick recap of what we\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'ve learnt today. In summary\r\nwe learnt that:\r\n\r\nA. Scientists use experiments to test their ideas\r\n\r\nB. A hypothesis is brought forward before experiments are\r\ncarried out to suggest a possible explanation.\r\n\r\nC. Chemistry like every other thing has down sides to it.\r\n\r\nD. And my personal favourite, chemistry is fun and an\r\nessential science course for our world today.\r\n\r\nI would like you to take some minutes to answer the\r\nfollowing questions to test your knowledge of today\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\'s lesson. \r\n\r\n1. What is chemistry?\r\n\r\n2. Explain why we study chemistry. \r\n\r\n3. List the scientific methods in their order and explain\r\nthem\r\n\r\n4. Describe at least four applications of chemistry to man.\r\n\r\nSee you in my next lesson, bye!', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=er-l_GlJa2k', 'page', '1613242851Generic UP Web Merchant Integration Guide.pdf', 1, '46', '44ef829c-3487-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(3, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Matter, elements, compounds and mixtures.', 'a506b40d-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Welcome back!In our last class we talked about what chemistry is, why we study chemistry, the applications of chemistry and the scientific methods. We also briefly talked about matter. Today we\\\'ll be focusing on matter, its nature and properties. Also we\\\'ll focus on elements, compounds and mixtures. Sit tight, cos this module promises to be interesting.There are varying number of substances across the globe with different properties - be it physical or chemical - these substances exhibit different states, that is the solid liquid and gaseous states. We\\\'ll be considering these states in another lesson. In this lesson however, we\\\'re gonna be dealing with matter, and at the end of the lesson, you should be able to:A. Identify what matter is and is not.B. Describe the properties of matter.&amp;nbsp;C. Explain what elements, compounds and mixtures are.What is matter?Matter as we defined in our last class is anything that has mass and occupies space. All forms of matter are chemical substances which are of two types, the physical and chemical types. By this definition its obvious to us that almost everything we see on earth consists of matter. Take an apple for instance, it has mass seeing as you can weigh it on a weighing balance and in turn record its value. It also occupies space, this is because if you place the apple in a bowl, it covers a certain volume of that bowl. This goes to show that an apple is an example of matter.The mass of an object is expressed as the quantity of matter an object contains and is the same everywhere in the world. If I measure a certain substance\\&quot;A\\&quot; in Nigeria and I measure that same substance in Kenya, the substance will have the same mass. Its weight on the other hand could vary.Properties of Matter.To identify a substance, we look at its features, characteristics or properties. Properties of Matter include factors that can be measured, such as height, mass, length, density etc. We have two types, the physical and chemical properties of matter.Physical properties.Physical property or Extrinsic property as the name implies, is the morphological appearance of matter which includes colour, taste, solubility, density etc. These properties can be observed with our eyes.For example, Oxygen gas has the following physical properties:It is colourless, odourless and tasteless&amp;nbsp;It is soluble in waterIt is 21% abundant in natureChemical properties.Chemical properties or Intrinsic properties are properties that cannot be seen with our physical eye, but are inherent within the matter under observation. These properties represent the true nature of matter. These properties include: action on litmus, reaction with metals and non-metals etc.For example, the chemical properties of Oxygen gas includes:Their reaction with metal: oxygen reacts with metals to form their oxides.Action on litmus paper: oxygen is neutral to litmus paper&amp;nbsp;Reaction with non-metals: oxygen reacts with non-metals like carbon to form carbon monoxide etc.&amp;nbsp;Changes in NatureChanges occur daily in nature, these can be classified into two main types:Physical change and&amp;nbsp;Chemical changePhysical change: a physical change is one that can be easily reversed and in which there\\\'s no formation of new substances. Matter exists in three different states, solid, liquid and gas. You can obviously see that the tea you had for breakfast is liquid, and this can be changed to a different state by application or removal of heat. Take water for instance, when you heat it up,&amp;nbsp; it begins to evaporate when it reaches boiling point - it changes to gas - this same water can be put in a freezer, thus it changes to solid. All these change of states can be easily reversed and doesn\\\'t call for the formation of a new substance.Therefore, physical changes include: melting of solids to liquids, freezing of liquids to solids, sublimation of solids to gas, vapourization of liquids to gas, dissolution of common salt in water etc.Chemical change: a chemical change is one which is not easily reversed, and new substances are always formed. If you burn a piece of wood, it decomposes eventually. Can you reverse this reaction? That\\\'s a big no. You cannot turn the Ash and gases that are now byproducts back to the initial wood. Another example is rusting of iron, a burnt matchstick etc. These are all irreversible reactions.In summary the comparing properties of physical and chemical changes are:S/NPhysical Changes&amp;nbsp;Chemical Changes1It is easily reversibleIt is not easily reversible&amp;nbsp;2No formation of new substance&amp;nbsp;New substances are formed here3No mass change in the substance&amp;nbsp;The substance changes in mass4No considerable amount of heat change is involved, the heat change is latent ie hidden.&amp;nbsp;There is a considerable amount of heat change involved.&amp;nbsp;Elements.Elements consists of the building blocks of other substances in nature. Scientists over the years have discovered a little over a hundred elements, 94 of which are found occurring naturally in nature, such as metals which can be mined and extracted from their ores and others that do not occur naturally, these are made in the laboratory.As of this year, the year 2020, there are 118 known elements. Elements are grouped in what we call a periodic table. Elements are generally grouped into 4, namely:MetalsNon - metalsMetalloids&amp;nbsp;Nobel gases or rage gases. We will be exploring this topic at a later time.So, an element is a substance which cannot be split into simpler units by an ordinary chemical process. Imagine trying to split Nitrogen through physical means, impossible right?!Compounds.A compound is a chemical substance formed when two or more elements are chemically combined in a fixed proportion by mass. Take the water molecule for instance, it is chemically denoted as H2O. That is, it has 2 molecules of hydrogen and 1 molecule of oxygen. Therefore, the proportion by mass of the water molecule is 2:1. The elements, oxygen and hydrogen are combined by chemical means, so to separate it we will have to implore chemical processes.&amp;nbsp;A substance is formed as a result of a chemical change and usually has different properties from those of the substance it was formed from.Therefore, a compound is simply defined as a substance which contains two or more elements chemically combined together.Examples of compounds include:S/NCompoundsChemical formularConstituent elements1.&amp;nbsp;WaterH2OHydrogen and oxygen&amp;nbsp;2.Ammonia&amp;nbsp;NH3Nitrogen and hydrogen.&amp;nbsp;3.Limestone [calcium carbonate (IV)]&amp;nbsp;CaCO3&amp;nbsp;Calcium, carbon and oxygen.&amp;nbsp;4.Sand (Silicon dioxide)&amp;nbsp;SiO2Silicon and oxygen.&amp;nbsp;5.Sulphuric acid or Tetraoxosulphate(IV) acidH2SO4Hydrogen, sulphur and oxygen.&amp;nbsp;Mixtures.A mixture contains two or more constituents, physically combined together. A mixture unlike compounds are combined physically and thus are easily separable. A mixture can be homogeneous, this is one that is uniformly blended together, examples are blood, urine, sweat etc. Or it can be heterogeneous, that is one that is not uniformly blended together, this mixture is in layers of different constituents, examples starch, milk, limestone solution etc.Constituents of mixture.S/NTypesMixtureConstituents1.HomogeneousBloodWater, haemoglobin, fat, oil, blood cells, sugar, protein, hormones, mineral salt, vitamins, enzymes.2.UrineUrea, water, mineral salt.3.SweatAmmonium salt, water4.HeterogeneousStarchStarch, water5.&amp;nbsp;MilkWater, sugar, vitamins fat, protein, mineral salt.6.Limestone solution&amp;nbsp;Limestone (Calcium trioxocarbonate(IV) and water.Comparison of compounds and mixturesS/NCompoundMixture1.Can be separated by chemical meansCan be separated by physical means.&amp;nbsp;2.&amp;nbsp;It is always homogeneousIt can be homogeneous or heterogeneous.&amp;nbsp;3.&amp;nbsp;It can be represented by a chemical formular because its constituents are in a fixed proportion by massIt cannot be represented by a chemical formular because constituents are combined in different proportion by mass.&amp;nbsp;4.The property of a compound is entirely different from those if its constituent elements&amp;nbsp;The property of a mixture is the sum total of its constituents.&amp;nbsp;In summary, we learnt that:1. Matter is anything that has mass and occupies space, it has varying properties, both chemical and physical properties.2. An element is a substance which cannot be split into simpler units by an ordinary chemical process. Imagine trying to split Nitrogen through physical means, impossible right?!3. A compound is simply defined as a substance which contains two or more elements chemically combined together.4. A mixture contains two or more constituents, physically combined together.&amp;nbsp;I encourage you to answer the questions below to ensure mastery of this lesson.&amp;nbsp;1. What is matter?2. What are the properties of matter, both physical and chemical?&amp;nbsp;3. Describe elements, compounds and mixtures in your own words.I hope you enjoyed this lesson like I did. See you soon!&amp;nbsp;', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OWsEm5W7G5U&amp;feature=youtu.be', 'page', '', 1, '', '39fb796f-348b-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(4, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Atoms, molecules and ions. ', 'a506b40d-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Atoms, molecules and ionsHello and welcome back!In our last lesson we looked at matter, its properties, elements, compounds and mixtures. Today we\\\'ll be focusing on atoms, molecules and ions. We\\\'ll also be looking at the Dalton\\\'s atomic theory and it\\\'s modification.At the end of the lesson, you should be able to:1. Explain what atoms molecules and ions are2. State the postulates of Dalton\\\'s atomic theory3. Explain the modifications to the atomic theory.Before we begin, remember from our last lesson that an element is a substance that can be split into simpler units by an ordinary physical process. And a compound is substance that consists of two or more elements chemically combined together.Atoms.Substances can be split into really tiny particles again and again. Take an apple for instance, if you divide it in two and you divide one half of it in two and pick another half to divide in two and you continue the process, there will almost always be a tiny particle to divide. Each of these tiny particles have the same properties with the whole apple ie. both the small and big apple all have the same constituents in them, its just that they both have it in different quantities. I want you to imagine that whole apple as an element, the atoms of that element is the little pieces of the apple. Meaning the tiny apple piece is the atom and the big whole apple is the element. That\\\'s why we hear things like, the atom of an element.Element - the big whole (apple)Atom - the tiny apple piece.Just as the basic units that make up the whole apple is the little pieces, so also the basic unit that makes up an element is an atom(s).Therefore, an atom is the smallest particle of an element that can take part in a chemical reaction. So, no matter how tiny atoms are, they each still have the properties of that element, such that they can take part in a chemical reaction.&amp;nbsp;Molecules.&amp;nbsp;Imagine I have a substance like garri in a bowl, and I scooped some of it. The scooped one in my hand still has the same chemical properties as the rest in the bowl. A molecule is like the garri in the bowl with multiple scoops of garri. These scoops can have the same or different particle size.A molecule is therefore, the smallest particle of a substance that can exist alone and still retain the chemical properties of that substance.Atoms generally cannot exist alone, they need other atoms to bond with to form a molecule. So we could have molecules from the same element, or different types of elements. A good example is the oxygen gas molecule and the water molecule. On the one hand the oxygen gas is made up of two oxygen atoms - same types of elements - on the other hand the water molecule is made up of hydrogen and oxygen - two different types of elements.The number of atoms in each molecule of an element is called the atomicity of that element. Gaseous elements are usually diatomic, meaning they have 2 atoms. Neon (Ne) for example has an atomicity of 1, hydrogen (H2) an atomicity of 2, ozone (O3) an atomicity of 3, Phosphorus (P4) an atomicity of 4, and Sulphur (S8) an atomicity of 8.Let\\\'s calculate the atomicity of the following molecules:1. Aluminium oxide (Al2O3)Aluminium has 2 atoms and oxygen gas 3 atom, making it a total of 5 atoms.2. Tetraoxosulphate(VI) acid (H2SO4)Hydrogen has 2 atoms, sulphur has 1 atom, and oxygen has 4 atoms, that makes a total of 7 atoms.Compounds generally exists as molecules. Therefore, that small particle that possess the chemical properties of a given compound is its molecules.Ions.Certain particles have charges and others do not, ions are particles that have electric charge. Ions is therefore any atom or group of atoms which possesses an electric charge. The two types of ions are the positively charged ions also known as the cations and the negatively charged ions also known as the anions.Dalton\\\'s Atomic Theory.&amp;nbsp;John Dalton in 1803, put forward a theory known as the atomic theory to explain the structure of an atom. He is regarded as the founding father of atomic discoveries, the first to elucidate the true structure of an atom. John Dalton\\\'s theory postulates that:1. All matter is made up of small indivisible particles called atoms.&amp;nbsp;2. Atoms can neither be created nor destroyed but can be changed from one form to another.&amp;nbsp;3. Atoms of the same elements are alike in every way but differ from atoms of other elements.&amp;nbsp;4. The combination of atoms is in simple ratio.&amp;nbsp;5. All chemical reactions results from the combination or the Separation of atoms.Modification of Dalton\\\'s atomic theory.We explained in our first lesson on introduction to chemistry that scientist came up with discoveries through scientific methods, the same is true for John Dalton. His atomic theory was proposed using observation, hypothesis and experiments. As a result of new discoveries Dalton\\\'s theory was found to be wanting in some areas. As a result, it was modified to what we have today.1. All matter is made up of small indivisible particles called atoms. Rutherford\\\'s discoveries proved this to be wrong. According to his discovery atom is made up of three sub-particles namely protons electrons and neutrons. This debunked the theory that atoms are made up of indivisible particles.&amp;nbsp;2. Atoms can neither be created nor destroyed but can be changed from one form to another. This postulate still holds true particularly for simple chemical reactions. In simple chemical reactions, new substances are formed, but no destruction of substances occurs. However, in complex reactions such as nuclear reactions, the nucleus of an atom of an element can be destroyed to create an atom of an entirely different element.3. Atoms of the same elements are alike in every way but differ from atoms of other elements. The discovery of isotopy as well as isotopes, shows that atoms of the same element may not exactly be alike. An isotopes of an element has same atomic number but different mass number. Chlorine for instance has two isotopes, both isotopes have atomic numbers of 17. Their mass numbers however are 35 and 37 respectively. I\\\'ll explain the concept of isotopy, better in the next lesson.4. The combination of atoms is in simple ratio. Not all compounds combine in small whole numbers, inorganic compounds generally do, with the exception of Silicon which forms very complex trioxisilicates(IV) with large numbers of atoms. Organic compounds however, contain large numbers of atoms, as much as thousands of atoms in substances such as protein fats etc.In summary, we learnt that:1. An atom is the smallest particle of an element that can take part in a chemical reaction.&amp;nbsp;2. A molecule is the smallest particle of a substance that can exist alone and still retain the chemical properties of that substance.3. Ions are particles that have electric charge.4. Dalton\\\'s atomic theory was modified to meet new discoveries.&amp;nbsp;Before we go let\\\'s look at the following questions.1. What is an atom, molecule and ion?2. Explain Dalton\\\'s atomic theory.3. Describe the modifications made to the theory.Don\\\'t know about you, but I sure had a wonderful time today. I hope to see you again!&amp;nbsp;', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gOOBwjL1MS0&amp;feature=youtu.be', 'page', '', 1, '', 'be958006-348b-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(5, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Atomic number, Isotopy and relative atomic mass. ', 'a506b40d-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Hello and welcome back!In our last lesson we explored atoms , molecules and ions as well as the Dalton\\\'s Theory and its modifications.&amp;nbsp;Today we\\\'ll be considering the constituents of atoms, atomic and mass number, isotopy, arrangement of electrons around the nucleus and the relative atomic mass.By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:1. Describe the constituents of atoms&amp;nbsp;2. Explain the concept of isotopy&amp;nbsp;3. Solve little problems on relative atomic masses.Composition of the atom.From our last lesson we defined atom as the smallest particle of an element which can take part in a chemical reaction.&amp;nbsp;Now, an atom has two main parts: the nucleus which is the centre of the atom and the shells, which surrounds the nucleus at a defined distance.The sub - atomic particles of an atom are protons, neutrons and electrons. The Electrons which are negatively charged are found on the shells, while the protons and neutrons which are positively and neutrally (no charge) charged respectively are found in the nucleus of the atom.The proton and neutron are the nuclear particles since they are found in the nucleus of an atom. They determine the atomic number and mass number of an atom. These numbers are always whole numbers.Atomic number, mass number and Isotopy.&amp;nbsp;The atomic number is the number of protons in the nucleus of an atom. It is denoted as, Z. The mass number however, is the sum of the proton and neutron numbers, in the nucleus of an atom. It is denoted as, A.Atomic number is same as the atomicity = number of protonsMass number = protons + neutronsTake Aluminum for instance, it\\\'s atomic number is 13, but it\\\'s mass number is 27, meaning that it\\\'s neutron number is 14.Mass number = protons + neutrons27 = 13 +?&amp;nbsp;Neutron = 27 - 13 = 14.Also note that the proton number and electron number of a neutral atom has the same values, the only difference is in its electric charge. Protons are positively charged while electrons are negatively charged.In summary an atom has two parts the shell carrying the Electrons which are negatively charged and the nucleus consising of the protons (positively charged) and neutrons (no charge).Since we now know what atoms consists of, let\\\'s briefly look at isotopy for better understanding.Isotopy: this is the occurrence or existence of two or more atoms of the same elements having the same atomic number but different mass number.Isoptopes: are atoms of the same elements with same atomic number ie. same number of protons but different mass number ie. different number of neutrons.Take the chlorine example sited earlier, their mass numbers are 35 and 37 respectively.Chlorine A has atomic number of 17 and mass number of 18.This is expressed as 35 - 17 = 18.&amp;nbsp;Therefore, chlorine A has a mass number of 18.Chlorine B has atomic number of 17 and mass number of 20.This is expressed as 35 - 17 =&amp;nbsp; 20.Therefore, chlorine B has a mass number of 20.3517 Cl&amp;nbsp; 3717 ClRelative atomic mass.&amp;nbsp;When we say something is relative it means, that thing is connected to or depending on something else. This means, it takes its bearing from it. Scientists use carbon - 12 as a reference point for measuring atomic masses. The concept of Carbon - 12 is the standard used by scientists from which atomic masses of all nuclides are measured. Therefore, its atomic mass is exactly 12 Daltons by definition. Carbon-12 has equal numbers of protons, neutrons, and electrons.&amp;nbsp;Relative atomic mass is a ratio, it has no unit, rather it is expressed in unit of amount of a substance. Every isotope of an element has its own mass, this is known as the isotopic mass.Therefore, relative atomic mass of an element is defined as the weight in grams of the number of atoms of the element contained in 12.00 g of carbon-12. It is the number of times, the average mass of one atom of element is heavier than one - twelfth (1/12 th) the mass of one atom of 12 grams of carbon 12.To measure relative atomic mass of an element, we use an instrument called the mass spectrometer.There are several ways to calculate the relative atomic mass using isotopes:Percentage abundance givenRelative atomic mass = [mass number of the first isotope X its abundance / 100 + mass number of the second isotope X its abundance / 100] + depending on the number of isotopes.&amp;nbsp;Ratio givenRelative atomic mass = [mass number of isotope X its ratio / total ratio + mass number of the second isotope X its ratio / total ratio] + depending on the number of isotopes.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s look at the following examples.&amp;nbsp;1. Chlorine exist in isotopic mixtures of 3517 Cl and 3717 Cl with a relative abundance of 75% and 25% respectively. What is the relative atomic mass of chlorine?Solution.Relative atomic mass = [mass number of isotope X its abundance / 100]+ depending on the number of isotopes.Relative atomic mass, RAM =?&amp;nbsp;Mass no of the 1st isotope = 35, its abundance = 75%Mass number of the 2nd isotope =37, it\\\'s abundance = 25%RAM = [35 X 75 / 100] + [37 X 25 / 100]= 2625 / 100 + 925 / 100= 26.25 + 9.25 = 35.52. Chlorine exist as 35 and 37 with the relative atomic mass of 35.5. Calculate the relative percentage abundance of the two isotopes.Solutions.Relative atomic mass = [mass number of isotope X its abundance / 100]+ depending on the number of isotopes.Relative atomic mass, RAM = 35.5&amp;nbsp;Mass no of the 1st isotope = 35, let its abundance be = x%Mass number of the 2nd isotope =37, let it\\\'s abundance = 100 - x %35.5 = [35 X x / 100] + [37 X 100 - x / 100]35.5 = 35x / 100 + 37(100 - x) / 10035.5 = 0.35x + 0.37 (100 - x)35.5 = 0.35x + 37 - 0.37x35.5 - 0.37 = 0.35x - 0.37x-1.5 = - 0.02xX = 1.5 / 0.02 = 75%The percentage of Chlorine 35 is 75%The percentage of chlorine 37 is (100 - x)&amp;nbsp;100 - 75) = 25%In summary we learnt that:1. Atoms has two main parts, the nucleus and the shell. The nucleus consists of protons and neutrons and the shell has electrons orbiting it.2. Relative atomic mass is a ratio, it has no unit, rather it is expressed in unit of amount of a substance.3. Isotopy is the occurrence or existence of two or more atoms of the same elements having the same atomic number but different mass number.Before we go, here are some practice questions.1. What are the constituents of atoms?2. Describe the concept of isotopy.3. Chlorine atoms exist with a mass number 35 and 37 in the ratio of 3 : 1. Calculate the relative atomic mass of chlorine.I encourage you to solve as many questions as possible on relative atomic mass.I had a swell time. Did you? I hope to see you soon, bye!&amp;nbsp;', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvkprMdRHuM', 'page', '', 1, '', 'cce2ed77-348c-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(6, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Relative molecular mass, mole and molar mass', 'a506fec9-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Hello!&amp;nbsp;In our previous lesson we discussed about atomic numbers, Isotopy and Relative atomic mass. Join me today, as we deal with the relative molecular mass, mole and the molar mass. At the end of this lesson its expected that you should be able to:1. Explain the relative molecular mass and solve questions on it.2. Describe the mole concept and solve problems relating to it.3. Explain molar mass and solve problems related to it.Relative molecular mass.&amp;nbsp;In our last lesson we defined the relative atomic mass as the number of times, the average mass of one atom of element is heavier than one - twelfth (1/12 th) the mass of one atom of 12 grams of carbon 12 (isotope).The relative molecular mass is the sum of the relative atomic masses of all the atoms in one molecule of that substance. The relative molecular mass is culled from the relative atomic mass.&amp;nbsp;Therefore, the relative molecular mass is the&amp;nbsp; number of times, the average mass of one molecule of element is heavier than one - twelfth (1/12 th) the mass of one molecule of 12 grams of carbon 12 (isotope).Mole.Think of a mole as a currency, the mole is an amount of a substance and a currency whatever the currency may be, is the purchasing power. Take the Naira for instance. A Naira = 100 kobos. So if we want to know how many kobos we have in 10 Naira, we\\\'ll multiply by a hundred, that will give us a thousand kobos. So also, if we want to know how many Naira we have in 3500 kobo, we divide by a hundred, which will yield 35 Naira.Just like Naira which is measured in kobo, Mole is measured in terms of the number of particles of a substance. A mole is a convenient method of expressing the amount of a substance. It is the unit of measurement for amount of substance in the International System of Units.One mole of a substance is the amount containing as many elementary entities as the number of atoms in exactly 12 grams of carbon 12.&amp;nbsp;Therefore, a mole of a substance or a mole of particles is defined as exactly 6.02Ã—10Â²Â³ particles, which may be atoms, molecules, ions, or electrons. Simply put 1 mol = 6.02Ã—10Â²Â³ particles.One mole of a substance is one particle, whether its a molecule - whole or not - an atom or ions.This, H- &amp;nbsp;is one molecule of hydrogen ionNH3 is one mole of ammonia molecule containing, one mole of Nitrogen and one mole of hydrogen6K is 6 moles of potassium atom&amp;nbsp;3N2 is 3 moles of Nitrogen molecules or 6 molecules of Nitrogen atom.Molar mass.&amp;nbsp;The molar mass of a substance is the mass of one mole of that substance expressed in grams. It is expressed as g/mol. Therefore the molar mass of an element, is its relative atomic mass expressed in grams and the molar mass of a compound, is its relative molecular mass expressed in grams.Formula\\\'s connecting moles and molar mass:1 mole of a substance is = its molar massExamples:1. Calculate the molar mass and the relative molecular mass of tetraoxosulphate(VI) acid, H2SO4. (H = 1, S = 32, O = 16)Solution.&amp;nbsp;H2SO4 = [1 x 2 + 32 + 16 x 4]= 2 + 32 +64= 98The molar mass is 98 g/mol and the relative molecular mass is 98, this is because molar mass is expressed in g/mol and relative molecular mass has no unit.2. How many moles are in 3.89g of ammonia, NH3? (N = 14, H = 1)Reacting mass = 3.89 gMolar mass of NH3 = 14 + 3 x 1 = 17 g/mol=&amp;nbsp; 0.228&amp;nbsp;= 0.23 mol&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;ORIf 1 mole of NH3 = 17 gX mole = 3.89 g=&amp;nbsp; 0.228&amp;nbsp;= 0.23 molMolar - Volume relationship.Calculate the volume present in 2.4g of sulphur(IV) oxide, SO2. (S = 32, O = 16).Equating both equations we have that:&amp;nbsp;Reacting mass = 2.4 gMolar mass of SO2 = 32 + 2 x 16 = 64 g/molReacting vol =?Molar vol = 22.4 dm3 (constant: gases at s.t.p occupy a volume of 22.4 dm3).&amp;nbsp;= 0.84 dm3.Let\\\'s take a recap of today\\\'s lesson, we learnt that:1. The relative molecular mass is the sum of the relative atomic masses of all the atoms in one molecule of that substance.&amp;nbsp;2. One mole of a substance is the amount containing as many elementary entities as the number of atoms in exactly 12 grams of carbon 12.&amp;nbsp;3. The molar mass of a substance is the mass of one mole of that substance expressed in grams. It is expressed as g/mol.Before we conclude, please answer the following questions:1. Define and explain the relative molecular mass, mole and the molar mass.2. Calculate the molar mass and the relative molecular mass of MgSO4 and Ca(HCO3)2. (Mg = 24, S = 32, O = 16, Ca = 40, H = 1, C =12).3. How many moles are in 8.3g of Carbon(IV)oxide, CO2? (N = 14, H = 1).Be sure to get your brain cracking by solving these problems.I\\\'ll be right back!', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nrbQYzx0jr0', 'page', '', 1, '', '7c311c57-348d-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0);
