(7, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Empirical formula, valency and balancing of chemical equations.', 'a506fec9-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'In the previous lesson we looked at relative molecular mass, mole and molar mass and we solved some problems relating to them.Today we will be focusing on empirical formula, molecular formula, Valency and balancing of chemical equations.At the end of the lesson, you should be able to;Explain the concept of empirical and molecular formula and&amp;nbsp; solve problems relating to themExplain valencyBalance chemical equations.EMPIRICAL FORMULA AND MOLECULAR FORMULA.&amp;nbsp;Empirical formula.This is the simplest formula of a compound. It expresses the simplest ratio of the element of a compound.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The following are steps taken in deriving the empirical formula of a compound;Step 1: calculate the percentage composition of each element of the compound if it\\\'s not given, for a carbohydrate for instance. This an organic compound containing three elements carbon hydrogen and oxygen in which hydrogen and oxygen combine in the ratio 2 is to 1 as in water. Step 2: divide each percentage composition of each element by their respective atomic masses.Step 3: divide through by the smallest decimal fractions and write their ratios.Note: if the ratio of any of the elements is in decimal place such as 0.5 1.5 2.5 etc. do not approximate to the nearest whole number but rather multiply each ratio by 2 for every other ratio approximate to the nearest whole number.Step 4: take the whole number as a subscript of each chemical symbol of each elements to give the empirical formula.Molecular formula.The molecular formula of a compound is the actual formula of a compound. It is expressed as the actual mass of element as contained in a compound.To calculate the molecular formula the following steps are taken:Step 1: calculate the empirical formula of the compoundSteps 2: calculate the positive integer, n from the expression&amp;nbsp;ORStep 3: substitute the positive integer, n with the expression below and multiply it with the subscript of the empirical formula to give the molecular formula.&amp;nbsp;Example.An organic compound contains 40% of carbon 6.67% of hydrogen and the rest is oxygen having a relative molecular mass of 60. Calculate:a. its empirical formulab. its molecular formulaSolution&amp;nbsp;CHOStep 1: % composition40%6.67%100 -â€“ (40 + 6.67) = 53.33%Step 2: divide by its atomic number40/12 =3.33&amp;nbsp;6.67/1 =6.6753.33/16 =3.33Step 3: divide by the smallest fraction&amp;nbsp;3.33/3.33 = 1	6.67/3.33 = 23.33/3.33 = 1	1:2:1Empirical formula = C1H2O1&amp;nbsp;= CH2OStep 1:&amp;nbsp; Empirical formula = CH2OStep 2: calculate n(CH2O)n = 60(12 + 2 x 1 + 16)n = 6030n =60n = 2Differences between empirical formula and molecular formula.S/NEmpirical formulaMolecular formula1.It is the simplest formula of a compoundIt is the actual formula of a compound2.It expresses the ratio in which the elements of a compound is combinedIt shows the actual percentage mass of an element of a compoundVALENCYElectrons have completely filled outer shells and incompletely filled outer shells. The Electron in an incompletely filled outer shell of an atom is called valence electron.&amp;nbsp; Atoms combine because of valence electrons. They do so to fulfill the duptet and octet rule. Because atoms are supposed to have two electrons or eight electrons respectively on its outermost shell to be balanced an atom with less than eight electrons in its outermost shell, is imbalanced.We have two kinds of elements, reactive and unreactive elements.If you have an ice cream cone, I hope you know that the tendency of the ice cream to melt is high particularly on hot days. The reactive elements are like the melted ice cream, which is incomplete (on its surface). So also, reactive elements have incomplete electrons on its outermost shell.The unreactive elements are known as noble gases or the rare gases. They have complete number of outer shell electrons and are therefore stable.&amp;nbsp;Valency is the combining power of an element. Elements in the same group of the periodic table have the same valency. And a valence electron is an outer shell electron of an atom that can participate in the formation of a chemical bond.To write the valency of an element the outermost electrons or valence electrons is considered after distributing the electrons in shell.&amp;nbsp; Electrons revolve around the nucleus of an atom in elliptical orbits called shells or energy levels. The shells or energy levels are lettered K, L, M, N... being the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th... shells of the nucleus respectively. The maximum number of electrons in each shell is assigned a formula 2n2 where â€˜nâ€™ is the position of the shell.Note: according to IUPAC (international union of pure and applied chemists) the M shell should contain a maximum of eight electrons for the first 30 elements. The noble, rare or inert gases are the most unreactive elements of the periodic table. This is because they have attained a complete octet configuration (8 valence electron configuration) with the exception of Helium atom which has the duptet configuration (2 valence electron configuration).Octet ruleThe octet rule states that elements will attain stability by giving out or accepting electrons to attain the eight valence configuration or the two valence configuration of the noble gases or the Helium atom respectively.If an element gives out electrons it becomes positively charged because the number of protons are more than the number of electrons. Hence the majority of charge carriers are positive charges. Similarly if an element accepts electrons it becomes negatively charged because the number of electrons is more than the number of protons. Hence the majority of charge carriers are negative charges.This can be simply illustrated with the principle of giving. It is often said that it is better to give than to receive, and it is also a common saying that givers never lack. So the element that gives electrons to another becomes positively charged and the one that receives electrons from another element becomes negatively charged.Balancing of Chemical Equations.Before we dive right in, what is a chemical equation?A chemical equation is a symbolic representation of a chemical reaction in the form of symbols and formulae, where the reactant entities are on the left-hand side and the product entities on the right-hand side.A chemical equation is like seesaw swing. I\\\'m sure you know what a seesaw is. It\\\'s that two - person seat, composed of a plank, balanced in the middle, used as a game in which one person goes up as the other goes down; a teeter-totter. It is common on most playgrounds. In a chemical equation we have both the reactants and products side just like the seesaw, and both sides want to be properly comfortable i.e. balanced.Remember in our lesson on the modifications to Daltonâ€™s atomic theory, we looked at the law of Conservation of matter which states that matter can neither be created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction. An unbalanced chemical equation shows that atoms have being created or destroyed. Therefore in other to obey the law of conservation of matter all chemical equations must be properly balanced.In balancing chemical equations, the following rules must be adhered to:Do not for any reason touch the formulae of the reactants and productsBalance the reaction by adding to the number of moles of the reactant and product sideDo a count to ensure that the number of atoms of a certain element at the reactant side equals that on the product side.Here are some examples.Balance the following chemical equations:1. Let\\\'s begin with a simple one, the formation of water molecule.H2(g) + O2(g) - H2O(l)All of the reactants and product have a coefficient of 1. Therefore weâ€™ll start by adding 2 to hydrogen on the LHS while also trying to balance the number of hydrogen on the RHS with whatever number that is suitable.2H2(g) + O2(g)  H2O(l)The hydrogen on the LHS is 4 and on the RHS is 2, to balance it out we add 2, to the one on the RHS.2H2(g) + O2(g)  2H2O(l)Next thing we do is to look at the other reactants and products. In this case we have no other product, the reactants on the other hand is 2. We have dealt with the hydrogen gas, the other one is the oxygen gas and it is seen to be balanced both on the LHS and RHS. In total we have 2 oxygen on the LHS and 2 oxygen on the RHS.Therefore the balanced chemical equation of that reaction is;2H2(g) + O2(g)  2H2O(l)2. Methane gas and oxygen gas combines to give us carbon dioxide and water molecule.CH4(g) + O2(g) &amp;nbsp; CO2(g) + H2O(g)Carbon has the same value on the LHS and RHS.Hydrogen on the other hand is 4 on the LHS and 2 on the RHS. Therefore we add 2 to the water molecule to balance the number of hydrogen on both sides. We now haveCH4(g) + O2(g)  CO2(g) + 2H2O(g)Oxygen is 2 on the LHS and 4 in total on the RHS, it is 4 because, in carbon dioxide oxygen is 2 and in water, oxygen is 2, making a total of 4. Therefore we add 2 to the oxygen gas on the LHS to balance the number of oxygen on both sides. We now have;CH4(g) + 2O2(g)  CO2(g) +2 H2O(g)Therefore the balanced chemical equation of that reaction is;CH4(g) + 2O2(g)  CO2(g) +2 H2O(g)Note: ionic chemical equations can also be balanced, we will study this at a later time.&amp;nbsp;Importance of a chemical equation.&amp;nbsp;The importance of chemical equations cannot be overemphasized. Its importance are:a. It helps us to see the reactants and products involved in a reaction. The reactants are located on the left hand side (LHS) and the products on the right hand side (RHS) of the reaction.b. It tells us to know the direction of the reaction, whether the reaction is reversible or irreversible.c. It also tells us the different elements and radicals involved in the reaction.d. It gives us the states of matter in which the substances are in for example liquid, solid or gaseous states.In summary we learnt that:Empirical formula is the simplest formula of a compound and molecular formula is the actual formula of a compound.The mathematical relationship between empirical formula and the molecular formula is given as molecular formula = (empirical formula)nValency&amp;nbsp; is the combining power of an element .Balancing of chemical equations is very important because an unbalanced chemical equation shows that atoms have been created or destroyed which is impossible.Before we leave let\\\'s take these questions :What is empirical and molecular formula and valency?State the importance of balancing chemical equations.An compound contains 29.11% of sodium 40.51% of sulphur and the rest is oxygen. It has a vapor density of 79. Calculate its empirical formula and molecular formula respectively.&amp;nbsp;(Na = 23, S = 32, 0 = 16).As much as you can, solve questions relating to empirical formula, molecular formula and balancing of chemical equations.See you some other time.&amp;nbsp;', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GqCJrslEGZA', 'page', '', 1, '', '03983c09-348e-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(8, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Percentage composition, oxidation state and Radicals', 'a506fec9-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Good day!So, we\\\'ve looked at matter empirical and molecular formula, Valency and balancing of chemical equations.Today we\\\'ll move on to look at Percentage composition, oxidation states and radicals. At the end of the lesson you should be able to:1. Determine the percentage composition by mass of compounds2. Determine the oxidation number of compounds and&amp;nbsp;3. Also describe radicals.Percentage CompositionThe percentage composition by mass of a compound helps us to determine the percentage by mass of each element present in the compound. So what we do is to get percentage composition by an individual element of the compound over all the other elements in the compound.Let\\\'s take some examples.Calculate the percentage composition by mass of sodium and oxygen in:a. NaNO3b. Na2CO3.10H2O(Given that Na = 23, N = 14, O = 16, C = 12, H = 1)a. NaNO3% by mass of sodium of NaNO3 =NaNaNO3  x 100% =2323+14+3x16  x 100%&amp;nbsp;=2385  x 100%&amp;nbsp;= 0.27 x 100 = 27%% by mass of oxygen in NaNO3 =3ONaNO3  x 100%=3x1623+14+3x16  x 100%&amp;nbsp;=4885  x 100%&amp;nbsp;= 0.565 x 100 = 56.5%b. Na2CO3.10H2O% by mass of sodium in Na2CO3.10H2O=2NaNa2CO3.10H2O x 100%=2x232x23+12+3x16+10(2x1+16)  x 100%&amp;nbsp;=46286  x 100%&amp;nbsp;= 0.161 x 100 = 16.1%% by mass of sodium in Na2CO3.10H2O=23ONa2CO3.10H2O x 100%=2x162x23+12+3x16+10(2x1+16)  x 100%&amp;nbsp;=48286  x 100%&amp;nbsp;= 0.168 x 100 = 16.8%Note: we can calculate the individual elements in every compound. For instance, in Na2CO3.10H2O we can calculate the sodium, carbon, oxygen elements in the compound and also the percentage composition of the water molecule in the compound.Oxidation Number/StateThe oxidation number of an element in a compound or radical is the combining power of that element in the compound or radical. An oxidation state shows how many electrons an atom would gain or lose if it were to bond with other atoms or radicals.RadicalsA radical is a group of atoms that possess electrical charges. They are known as free radical, in chemistry. And they are molecules that contain at least one unpaired electron.Examples of radicals are:Hydroxide ion, which has a chemical formula OH-, has a valency of 1 and oxidation number of - 1.Tetraoxosulphate (VI) ion, which has a chemical formula SO42-, has a valency of&amp;nbsp; 2 and oxidation number of - 2.Consult the diagram here.&amp;nbsp;Remember, Valency is the number of electrons present in the outermost shell of a particular element whereas oxidation state is the number of electrons that an element in a particular compound has lost or gained.Therefore, Valency carries no charge but oxidation numbers always caries a positive or negative charge.&amp;nbsp;Rules for naming or assigning oxidation numberOxidation number can be assigned to elements, compounds, or radicals. Follow these rules in doing so.&amp;nbsp;1. Oxidation numbers can be positive and negative.2. The algebraic sum of all valency of elements in a compound equals zero.&amp;nbsp;3. The oxidation number of an element in an uncombined state or Free State is equal to zero.4. Oxidation number of hydrogen\\\'s in a compound is always +1 with an exception with metal hydrides like NaH where it is - 1.5. The oxidation number of oxygen in a compound is always - 2 except in peroxides like H2O2 where it is - 1.For example the oxidation states of oxygen, hydrogen, fluorine and aluminium is - 2, +1, -1 and +3 respectively. This follows rules 1, 4 and 5.Remember, most elements have the oxidation states of the group in which they fall into. For instance most group one element have an oxidation state of + 1, group 2 has that of + 2, group 3 that of + 3 and so on. Group 7 elements have the oxidation states of - 1 seeing as it gains an electron to become stable.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s take an example of NH3 and H2SO4.NH3 = - 3 + 3(1)= - 3 +3 = 0The oxidation number of Nitrogen varies from - 3 to +5, this is because Nitrogen can obtain a stable configuration by either gaining 3 electrons, thereby attaining oxidation state of -3, or losing all the 5 valence shell electrons, thus becoming +5.&amp;nbsp;H2SO4 = 2(1) + 6 + 4(-2)= 2 + 6 - 8 = 0This follows all the rules.Note: Some elements exhibit variable oxidation state these elements are mostly the transition elements also known as transition metals.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s consider the equations below:2Ho2(g) + Oo2(g) â†’ 2H+12 O2-(l)Uncombined - CombinedCa2+O2-(s) + C4+O2-2(g) â†’  Ca2+C4+O2-3(S)Combined statesNow let\\\'s calculate the oxidation states of some compounds and radicals.&amp;nbsp;1. KMnO41 + Mn + 4(-2) = 01 - 8 + Mn = 0Mn = +72. Cr2O72-2Cr + 7(-2) = - 22Cr - 14 = - 2Cr = 12/2Cr = +63. MnO42-Mn + 4(-2) = - 2Mn&amp;nbsp; - 8 = - 2Mn = 8 - 2 = +64. Fe(CN)63-Fe +6(- 1) = - 3Fe = 6 - 3 = +3We have come to the end of this lesson in summary we learnt that:The percentage composition by mass of a compound helps us to determine the percentage by mass of each element present in the compound.&amp;nbsp;Valency is the number of electrons present in the outermost shell of a particular element whereas oxidation state is the number of electrons that an element in a particular compound has lost or gained.Endeavour to solve the questions below.1. Calculate the percentage composition by mass of all the component elements in:a. Ca(OH)2b. H3PO4c. CuSO4.5H2O2. Calculate the oxidation states of the following compounds and radicals.a. MnO2b. H2SO4c. CrO42-Bye for now!', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2lD0IYzOHlc', 'page', '', 1, '', 'cac74a12-348e-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(9, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Naming of binary compounds. ', 'a506fec9-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Welcome back!We looked at percentage composition, oxidation states and radicals in our previous lesson.&amp;nbsp;Today we\\\'ll move on to look at naming of binary compounds, involving metals, non-metals and transition metals.At the end of the lesson you should be able to name binary compounds, those of metals non-metals and transition metals.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s beginNaming of binary compound involving non-metalsThe following steps are taken in naming binary compounds involving two non-metals:1. Calculate the oxidation state of the first non-metal in the binary compound.&amp;nbsp;2. Name the nonmetal without changing its name.&amp;nbsp;3. Write the oxidation state in roman numeral and enclose it in a bracket.4. Finally end the name of the compound with the oxidation number or any other number attached to it, ending it with \\\'ide\\\'.&amp;nbsp;Name the following binary compounds:1. SO2S + 2(-2) = 0S = +4Sulphur (IV) oxide2. N2O2N + (-2) = 0N = +2/2N = +1Nitrogen (I) oxide3. NON + (-2) = 0N = - 2Nitrogen (II) oxideWriting the chemical formulae of binary compounds involving two non-metals1. Write the chemical symbols of the individual elements in the compounds.2. Assign their valencies and interchange them to their subscript in the chemical formula of the binary compound.Write the chemical formula of the following:Sulphur (IV) oxideS &amp;nbsp; O+4 -2S2O4 = SO2Nitrogen (I) oxideN. O+1 - 2N2ONitrogen (II) oxideN. O-2 - 2NONaming of binary compound involving Transition metals and other metalsTransition elements are metals are elements between groups 2 and groups 3 of the periodic table.It has the following metallic properties such as ductility, malleability, lustrous nature, magnetic tendency, sonorous nature, high melting and boiling point, electrical and thermal conductivity.They exhibit variable oxidation states due to the presence of vacant 3d orbitals for filling by electrons. They form colored compounds and complex ions.Rules in naming binary compounds involving transition metals and metals in general1. Calculate the oxidation state of the transition Metal.&amp;nbsp;2. Write the name of the transition metal changing its composition.&amp;nbsp;3. Write the oxidation state in Roman Numerals next to the metal enclosed in a bracket.&amp;nbsp;4. Change the non-metals name ending with the suffix \\&quot;ide\\&quot;.Let\\\'s take some examples:V2O52V + 5(-2) = 0V = 10/2 = +5Vanadium (V) oxideFe2O32Fe + 3(-2) = 0Fe = 6/2 = +3Iron (III) oxide or you can also call it ferric oxide.Cu2O2Cu + -2 = 0Cu = +2/2 = +1Copper (I) oxideCa3N23Ca + 2(-3) = 0Ca = 6/2 = +2Calcium nitrideWriting the chemical formulae of binary compounds involving transition metals1. Write the chemical symbols of the individual elements in the compounds.2. Assign their valencies and interchange them to their subscript in the chemical formula of the binary compound.Write the chemical formula of the following:Vanadium (V) oxideV. O+5. - 2V2O5Iron (III) oxideFe&amp;nbsp; O+3 +2Fe2O3Copper (I) oxideCu. O+1.-2Cu2OCalcium nitrideCa&amp;nbsp; N+2&amp;nbsp; - 3Ca3N2We have come to the end of this lesson, let\\\'s take the summary.We learnt how to name binary compounds involving transition metals and other metals and the non-metals.&amp;nbsp;Endeavour to solve the questions below.1. Name the following binary compounds and write their chemical formulae:a. SO3b. Cu2Sc. VCl5d. Fe3O4e. MnO2See you soon, bye for now.', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', '48631870-348f-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(10, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, '. Naming of trinary compounds I.', 'a506fec9-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Hello!We looked at naming of binary compounds, involving metals, non-metals and transition metals.Today we\\\'ll move on to look at naming of trinary compounds involving acids and basesAt the end of the lesson you should be able to name trinary compounds, of acids and bases.We have three types of trinary compounds, those of acids, bases and salts.Naming of trinary compound involving inorganic acidsLet\\\'s first look at what an acid is.&amp;nbsp;An acid is a substance that dissolves in water to produce hydrogen ions H+ as the only positively charged ion.To name an inorganic acid, the following steps are taken:1. Calculate the oxidation states of the middle elements.2. Name the number of oxygen at the end using the words oxo, dio, trio all according to the number of oxygen in the compound.3. Name the middle elements ending with \\&quot;ate\\&quot;.4. Write the oxidation number in Roman numeral enclosed in bracket.5. Finally end the compound with the word \\\'acid\\\'.Name the following acidsH2CO32(+1) + C + 3(-2) = 0C + 2 - 6 = 0C = +4Trioxocarbonate (IV) acidHNO2+1 + N + 2(-2) = 0N = +3Dioxonitrate (III) acidH3PO43(+1) + P + 4(-2) = 0P = +5Tetraoxophosphate (V) acid&amp;nbsp;Writing the chemical formula of inorganic trinary acidsTo write the chemical formula of inorganic acid the following steps are taken:1. Outline hydrogen and the remaining radical.2. Write the oxidation state of hydrogen and the overall charge of the radicals.3. Interchange the numerical values to give the chemical formula of the acid.Trioxocarbonate (IV) acidH&amp;nbsp; CO3+1. -2H2CO3Dioxonitrate (III) acidH.&amp;nbsp; NO2+1. -1HNO2Tetraoxophosphate (V) acid&amp;nbsp;H. PO4+1. - 3H3PO4Note: There are inorganic acids that are binary compounds that do not follow the rules of naming binary compounds. They are hydrochloric acid, hydrochloric acid and hydroiodic acid.Naming of trinary compound involving bases/alkalisLet\\\'s quickly look at what a base and alkali is.&amp;nbsp;A base is a substance that dissolves in water to produce hydroxide ions as the only negatively charged ion. Alkalis are soluble bases.To name trinary base/alkali compounds, we folllow the following rules:1. Calculate the oxidation state of the unknown element.&amp;nbsp;2. Name the metal without changing its name.&amp;nbsp;3. Write the oxidation number in Roman numeral enclosed in bracket.4. Finally end the compound with the word \\\'oxide\\\' or \\\'hydroxide\\\'.&amp;nbsp;Fe(OH)2Fe + 2(-2) + 2(+1) = 0Fe - 4 + 2 = 0Fe = +2Iron (II) hydroxideNaOHNa - 2 + 1 = 0Na = +1Sodium hydroxide&amp;nbsp;FeOFe - 2 = 0Fe = +2Iron (II) oxideWriting chemical formulae of bases/alkalisTo write the chemical formula of bases/alkalis the following steps are taken:1. Name the metal.&amp;nbsp;2. Write the oxidation state3. Interchange the numerical values to give the chemical formula of the compound.Iron (II) hydroxideFe. OH+2. - 1Fe(OH)2Sodium hydroxideNa. OH+1. - 1NaOHIron (II) oxideFe. O+2. - 2FeOIn conclusion, we learnt how to name trinary compounds of acids and bases/alkalis.&amp;nbsp;Endeavour to solve the questions below.Name the following acids and bases:a. H2S2O3b. MgOc. HNO3d. Mg(OH)2e. MnO2Have a lovely day.&amp;nbsp;', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', '77abe005-348f-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(11, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Laws of chemical combination', 'a5072b1f-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Good to have you back!So far we have looked at the introduction to Chemistry, particulate nature of matter, Atoms, Moles, Formulae, Symbols and Chemical Equations.&amp;nbsp;Today we\\\'ll be focusing on the Laws of chemical combinations.At the end of the lesson you should be able to:1. State the laws of chemical combination2. Explain the laws of chemical combinations.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s begin.LAWS OF CHEMICAL COMBINATIONThe laws of chemical combination include;Law of conservation of mass or matterLaw of definite/constant/fixed proportionsLaw of multiple proportionsLaw of reciprocal proportionsThe law of conservation of massThis states that the total mass of a chemical system is constant or conserved. According to the law of conservation of matter, in ordinary chemical reactions matter can neither be created nor destroyed. This means the total mass of reactants in a chemical reaction equals the total mass of the products.&amp;nbsp;Heres an experiment to verify the law of conservation of mass. Mummy gives you a plate of beans and your sister a plate of rice. If you take a plate of your own beans and your sisters plate of rice and you weigh each separately on a weighing balance. You then mix them together and weigh their total sum, you will notice that the weight of each will be equal to the weight of both their sums. So also if you combine two elements like iron and sulphur,&amp;nbsp; you\\\'ll get iron sulphide. The individual masses of iron and sulphur is same as the combined mass of the iron sulphide.&amp;nbsp;Law of definite proportionsThis states that for all pure samples of the same chemical compound irrespective of the method of preparation, contain the same elements combined in the same proportion by mass.If Fola follows the standard recipe for baking a cake and Moji does the same, at the end we will have the same ratio for all the ingredients present. That is the flour to the magarine to the eggs to the sugar will all have the same values for both Fola\\\'s and Moji\\\'s cake.&amp;nbsp;So also, we know that water is always a combination of two atoms of hydrogen and one atom of oxygen. If we calculate the molecular mass of water we\\\'ll discover it to be 18 g/mol. By weight, we have a percentage of 11% hydrogen and 89% oxygen in one mole of water. This is in a ratio of 1:8. The Law of Definite Proportions illustrates that whatever the amount of water, the ratio of the amount of hydrogen to oxygen by weight will always be the same.Law of multiple proportionsThis is culled from Dalton\\\'s fourth law which states that atoms combine in small whole ratios. The law of multiple proportions states that if an element combines with another element to form more than one chemical compound the several masses of one element that combines with a fixed mass of another are in a simple or whole number multiple ratio.Lets take this illustration. We have different possible combinations of food. You could decide to eat rice, beans and stew with beef or jollof rice, plantain and goat meat. Just like different combinations are possible in food, different combinations are also possible for elements that make up compounds.Say we can combine element A to element B, that doesn\\\'t change the fact that, that same element A can be combined with another element C. Therefore, varying number of elements can combine with other elements to form different possible combinations.Law of reciprocal proportions&amp;nbsp;This states that if elements S, T, and U combine separately with a third element V, the ratio of the masses in which they combine are either the same or a simple multiple of the mass ratio in which they combine. The law simply means that if we know the proportion of elements in compounds ST and the proportion of elements in compounds UV, we can therefore determine the proportion of elements in compounds SV.&amp;nbsp; [ST + UV = TU + SV]Consider the equation below;2HCl(aq) + CaO(s)&amp;nbsp; CaCl2(aq) + H2O(l)1 : 35 + 20 : 8 20 : 35 + 1 : 8Look at hydrochloric acid, HCl, where the ratio is 1:35 and calcium oxide, CaO, where the ratio is 20:8. If we combine calcium and chlorine, we would expect to see a ratio of 20:35 and if we combine hydrogen and oxygen, we expect to see a ratio of 1:8. Yeah? This proves the law of reciprocal proportion to be true.Note: compounds can combine in a number of possible ways.In summary we learnt that:There are 4 laws of chemical combinationThey are, the laws of conservation of mass, the law of definite proportions, the law of multiple proportions and the law of reciprocal proportions.Make sure you learn to state each of these laws and explain them.&amp;nbsp;Be right back!&amp;nbsp;', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', '84e5b4d1-3495-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(12, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Quantum numbers and the electronic configuration.', 'a5072b1f-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'Hello!In our last class we looked at the Laws of chemical combinationsToday we\\\'ll be focusing on quantum numbers and the Electronic configuration of atoms of the first 20 elements.At the end of the lesson you should be able to:1. Explain the concept of quantum numbers&amp;nbsp;2. Describe the arrangement of electrons in an atom and3. Explain the electronic configuration of elements.Let\\\'s dive right in!QUANTUM NUMBERSI\\\'m sure you remember we said in a previous lessons that the nucleus consists of protons and neutrons and electrons is found orbiting the shell. Hydrogen atom however has no neutron. The isotopes of hydrogen are hydrogen with no neutron, deuterium with one neutron, and tritium with two neutrons , they all differ. Therefore, the hydrogen atom has a nucleus which consists of one proton and an electron orbiting its shell. The hydrogen atom has a number of orbits to choose from, but it sticks to the orbit with minimum energy. As the electrons continue to absorb energy it will rise on the energy level to an excited state. Different lines are produced depending on the orbits which the electrons fall on.&amp;nbsp;The Bohr\\\'s atom is denoted by the principal quantum number, n, which is a positive integer. The minimum energy level is denoted as n = 1, the next levels are n = 2, 3, 4, 5... to infinity, and each of these numbers are represented by letters K, L, M, N...The electron energy is usually characterized by the 4 quantum numbers - these quantum numbers give a detailed description of the electrons in an atom.The 4 quantum numbers are,1. The Principal quantum number, n, has integral values of 1, 2, 3, 4... Each represented by K, L, M, N... The principal quantum number n represents the relative overall energy of each orbital. The energy level of each orbital increases as its distance from the nucleus increases. Each shell is given as 2n2 and its total number of orbitals as n2.2. The subsidiary quantum number also known as azimuthal quantum number, l, has integral values ranging from 0 to (n - 1) ie. 0, 1, 2, 3 each represented by s, p, d, f. The subsidiary quantum number shows the energy subshells in a given energy level, it explains the principal quantum numbers properly.&amp;nbsp;3. The magnetic quantum number, m, has integral values ranging from - 1 through 0 to +1. This distinguishes the orbitals available within a subshell, (the subsidiary quantum number). For example, the p subshell has 3 p orbitals.4. The spin quantum number, s, has values of - 1/2 and +1/2. This quantum number describes the angular momentum of an electrons, ie. It shows the direction of orientation of an electron. Therefore, the electrons could spin on their axis in opposite directions.Principles of electron filling into orbitalsNow that we\\\'ve established that electrons are filled into orbitals and shells. We need to consider the rules that govern this filling process. We have 3 of these rules.1. Pauli\\\'s exclusion principle: this principle states that no two electrons in the same orbital can have the same values for all 4 quantum numbers. This means that, if 2 electrons have the same value for n (principal quantum number), m (subsidiary quantum number), and l (magnetic quantum number), they will differ in s (spin quantum number). Meaning no two electrons in an atom can behave in an identical manner.2. Hund\\\'s rule: this states that electrons occupy orbitals singly first before pairing in a degenerate orbital.&amp;nbsp; All electrons in a singly occupied orbital has the same spin.3. Aufbau\\\'s principle: this states that electrons enter into orbitals in order of increasing energy, starting from the lowest to the highest. You don\\\'t for example start grade 5 before you go ahead to grade 2, you rather move in a consistently increasing rate, from lowest to the highest grade.We\\\'ll take some examples in a bit for clearer understanding.Shapes of the s and p orbitalsHave you seen a soccer ball or basketball before? Maybe on a pitch. ThatÂ’s what a sphere looks like. Have you ever been to the gym? You must have seen a dumb bell there. A dumb bell is a piece of equipment used for weight lifting. It helps to build muscle, particularly around the arms. So, the s orbital is spherical in shape, and the p orbital has a dumb bell shape. See diagrams below.ARRANGEMENT OF ELECTRONS IN AN ATOM AND THE ELECTRONIC CONFIGURATIONThe arrangement of electrons in an atom is determined by the order of increasing energy level. Let\\\'s take a quick look at the first 20 elements of the periodic table (see diagram below).&amp;nbsp;Hydrogen has 1 electron and an atomic number of 1. Therefore the electron will occupy 1s subshell, to be 1s1. 1 is the principal quantum number, s is the subsidiary quantum number and 1, is the number of electrons of the hydrogen atom. The spin quantum number will point up, +1/2.LetÂ’s have an in-depth explanation to the 4 quantum numbers with these examples.The value of the principal quantum number, n, for K = 1, L = 2, M = 3, this follows its integral values. Note that the K shell has 2 electrons, the L shell, 8 electrons, the M shell, another 8 electrons etc. Therefore, if an element has 2 electrons, its principal quantum number will automatically be 1, if it has 6 electrons, its value will be 2, if it has 12 electrons its value will be 3. Or you could say that the coefficient of its electronic configuration is its principal quantum number.Consider the elements, Helium (He), Carbon (C), and Aluminum (Al).&amp;nbsp;In filling the electrons into its orbitals remember we must not forget the 3 rules involved.We have that;He = 1s2 having a total of 2 electrons. The value for the principal quantum number, n = 1 because the coefficient of 1s2 is 1. You can see the way the electrons are filled starting from the lowest energy level to the highest energy level, obeying Aufbau principle.C = 1s2, 2s2, 2p2 having a total of 6 electrons. The value for the principal quantum number, n = 2 because the coefficient of 2p2 is 2. You can see the way the electrons are filled starting from the lowest energy level to the highest energy level, obeying Aufbau principle. You can also see that we filled singly before coming right back to pair the electrons up, following&amp;nbsp; Hund\\\'s rule.Al = 1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s2, 3p1 having a total of 13 electrons. The value for the principal quantum number, n = 3 because the coefficient of 3p1 is 3. You can see the way the electrons are filled starting from the lowest energy level to the highest energy level, obeying Aufbau principle. You can also see that we filled singly before coming right back to pair the electrons up, following&amp;nbsp; Hund\\\'s rule.The value of the subsidiary quantum number, l for s subshell is 0, p subshell is 1, d subshell is 2 etc. This follows its integral values. Note that the s orbital has a maximum of 2 electrons, p orbital a maximum of 6 electrons, d orbital a maximum of 10 electrons and the f orbital with a maximum of 14 electrons.Consider the elements, Helium (He), Carbon (C), and Aluminum (Al) again.He = 1s2 the value for the subsidiary quantum number, l = 0. This is because for s subshell, l is 0.C = 1s2, 2s2, 2p2 the value for the subsidiary quantum number, l = 1. This is because for p subshell, l is 1.Al = 1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s2, 3p1 the value for the subsidiary quantum number, l = 2. This is because for d subshell, l is 2.	Note: Remember we said the integral values for the subsidiary quantum numbers are 0, 1, 2...Therefore, the values for the s subshell, l is 0, for p subshell, l is 1, for d subshell, l is 2 etc.The value for the magnetic quantum number ml, for s, when l = 0, is 0. For p, when l = 1 is 3 possible values of - 1, 0 and +1. For d, when l = 2 is 5 possible values of -2, - 1, 0, +1, +2 etc. Therefore, when filling the electrons we must follow HundÂ’s rule of filling singly before pairing.Consider the elements, Helium (He), Carbon (C), and Aluminum (Al) again.He = 1s2 the value for the magnetic quantum number, ml for s subshell which helium resides in = 0C = 1s2, 2s2, 2p2 the values for the magnetic quantum number, ml for p subshell which carbon resides in will give us 3 possible values of -1, 0 and +1.Al = 1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s2, 3p1 the values for the magnetic quantum number, ml for p subshell which aluminum resides in will give us 3 possible values of -1, 0 and +1.Note: the value for the magnetic quantum number, ml for s subshell is 0, for p subshell, it will give us 3 possible values of -1, 0 and +1, d subshell will give us 5 possible values of -2, -1, 0 +1 and +2, f subshell will give us 7 possible values of -3, -2, -1, 0, +1, +2 and +3.For the spin quantum number, s, we can have 2 possible values. The spin up which is +1/2and the spin down which is - 1/2.Consider the elements, Helium (He), Carbon (C), and Aluminum (Al) again.He = 1s2 the value for the spin quantum number, ms is -1/2, this is because the last electron that entered was a spin down electron.C = 1s2, 2s2, 2p2 the value for the spin quantum number, ms is +1/2, this is because the last electron that entered was a spin up electron.Al = 1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s2, 3p1 the value for the spin quantum number, ms is +1/2, this is because the last electron that entered was a spin up electron.In summary we learnt that:There are 4 laws of chemical combinationThere are 4 quantum numbers and we discovered how to deduce themElectrons are filled following certain rules.Before we leave let\\\'s take these questions:State the 4 laws of chemical combinationDescribe the 4 quantum numbersDeduce the quantum numbers for the first 20 elements in the periodic table.Write down the electronic configuration of the first 20 elements.See you some other time.&amp;nbsp;', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', 'f1db0e0f-349e-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(13, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Chemical combinations I.', 'a5072b1f-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'We looked at the laws of chemical combination, the quantum numbers and the electronic configuration in our last class, we will go right ahead to explore chemical combinations.It is a known fact that atoms bond. The atoms of rare gases are highly stable owing to their electronic configuration, and thus don\\\'t need to bond. The atoms of other elements however, are unstable, and they try to attain stability by chemical bonding.In chemical combinations, two types of bonds are formed:The intermolecular bonds, these are mostly strong bonds andThe intramolecular bonds, these are mostly weak bonds.&amp;nbsp;The intermolecular bonds are bonds that mostly occur between atoms of different elements. These are the main types of chemical combination, they include:1. Electrovalent/ionic combination2. Covalent combination, which is classified into:a. Ordinary Covalent combinationsb. Coordinate/Dative covalent combination.The intramolecular bonds mostly occur amongst atoms of the same elements. They are:1. Hydrogen bond2. Metallic bond3. Van der Waals forces.4. Dipole - dipole interaction.&amp;nbsp;In this lesson we will be looking at the strong bonds.ELECTROVALENT COMBINATIONThe main principle here is a donor - acceptor principle in which there is a complete electron transfer.If Chika needs a kidney transplant and Kelechi happens to have 2 healthy and functional kidneys. He could decide to give up one of his kidneys for Chika in order that Chika might live a healthy life. Kelechi is seen to be the donor while Chika is the acceptor.&amp;nbsp;In this type of bonding, there is a transfer of valence electrons from an electropositive element usually a metal, to an electronegative element usually a non - metal.&amp;nbsp;I hope you can still remember what valence electrons are? They are outermost shell electrons and they take part in chemical combinations. So, Kelechi who donates is electropositive while Chika who accepts, is electronegative.&amp;nbsp;Remember we said in a previous lesson that when you give, you are said to be on the plus side, and when you receive, you\\\'re on the minus side. So next time when you see your friend who has no pen and you have 2 working pens, why don\\\'t you be a good friend and give up one of your pens?Let\\\'s take some examples.Formation of Calcium chloride, CaCl2Ca(s) + Cl2(g)  CaCl2(s)The half equation for the reaction isCa  Ca2+ - 2e-AndCl2 + 2e-  Cl2-Joining both equations, we have that;Ca + Cl2 + 2e-  Ca2+ + Cl2-- 2e-Cancelling out the electrons on both sides, we have;CaCl2  Ca2+ Cl2-In bond formation, calcium has 20 electrons leaving 2 valence electrons for bonding; chlorine however, has 17 electrons, leaving 7 valence electrons for bonding. Just as it is easier for you to give your friend 2 naira, rather than a whopping 7 naira, so also it is easier for the calcium atom to give out its 2 valence electrons, than for the chlorine atoms to give out a whopping 7 electrons.&amp;nbsp; Therefore, calcium atom donates its 2 valence electrons to the 2 chlorine atoms available, hence making the calcium and chlorine to all be stable. The calcium atom is the donor, making it positively charged, while the chlorine is the acceptor, making it negatively charged.The number of neutrons and protons in a neutral and ionic atom is always the same, while the electron number always changes. This means that the number of proton and neutron in the calcium after bonding will remain the same. However, the electron number changes to 18 (20 â€“ 2), and the number of electrons for the chlorine atom changes to 18 (17 + 1). This makes both atoms to be stable and happy.Formation of sodium oxide, Na2O.&amp;nbsp;4Na(s) + O2(g)  2Na2O(s)The half equation for the reaction is4Na  4Na+ - 4e-AndO2 + 4e-  O22-Joining both equations, we have that;4Na + O2 + 4e-  4Na+ + O22- - 4e-Cancelling out the electrons on both sides, we have;4Na + O2 &amp;nbsp; 4Na+ + O22-In bond formation, sodium has 11 electrons leaving 1 valence electron for bonding; oxygen however, has 8 electrons, leaving 6 valence electrons for bonding.Therefore, the 2 sodium atoms donate their valence electrons to the oxygen atom available hence making the sodium and oxygen to all be stable. The sodium atom is the donor, making it positively charged, while the oxygen is the acceptor, making it negatively charged.The number of neutrons and protons in a neutral and ionic atom is always the same, while the electron number always changes. This means that the number of proton and neutron in the sodium after bonding will remain the same. However, the electron number changes to 10 (11 â€“ 1), and the number of electrons of the oxygen atom changes to 10 (8 + 2), making both atoms stable and happy.Properties of Electrovalent compounds1. They form ions in water; therefore they dissolve readily in water.2. They conduct electricity because of their dissociation to form ions, thatâ€™s why they are good electrolytes.&amp;nbsp;3. They have high melting and boiling points.&amp;nbsp;4. They occur mainly in inorganic compounds.5. They do not contain molecules.6. They exist mainly as solids at room temperature.&amp;nbsp;COVALENT COMBINATION&amp;nbsp;The main principle in covalent bond is that of sharing of electrons between atoms such that each of the atoms in a molecule has the electron arrangement of a noble gas. Take for instance, Banji has garri and Mensah has sugar they can both join their resources to have garri and sugar. If Fatima sees what is going on between them, she too can decide to bring her groundnut so that they can each have a taste of the entire combination. This is because in themselves the garri, sugar and groundnut isn\\\'t good enough, but as a whole it makes a beautiful meal of garri, sugar and groundnut.&amp;nbsp;Covalent combination occurs between two or more atoms of non - metals involving sharing of electrons to attain stability. Covalent bonding is divided into simple or ordinary covalent bonding and co-ordinate or dative covalent bonding.Ordinary Covalent BondingThis is the combination of two or more non-metals involving equal sharing of electrons to attain stability. The electrons donated for sharing are called shared pair electrons. The number of electrons shared during bonding is determined by the bond type, the bond structure and the bond angle.Nature of Bonds1. Formation of the oxygen moleculeOxygen atoms combine together to share their lone pair of electrons equally amongst themselves, to attain stability. Oxygen has 8 electrons and 6 valence electrons, meaning it needs 2 more electrons, both oxygen atoms share their lone electron pair equally to bring about stability. Before combination the 2 oxygen atoms have 8 electrons each, after combinations they each have 10 electrons making them stable.2. Formation of Ethene moleculeThe carbon atom and hydrogen atom, share their electron pairs equally to form ethene. The carbon atom before combination has six electrons and after combination has 10 electrons&amp;nbsp; and the hydrogen atom too, making them stable.The carbon atom shares 2 of its lone pairs of electrons, and the remaining 2 lone pairs are shared together with the hydrogen atom.COORDINATE/DATIVE COVALENT BONDINGThis is a type of covalent bonding that involves sharing of electrons between two combining atoms which mostly involve the bonding between a molecule and an ion in which the covalent molecule donates electrons for sharing. The electron involved is called the lone pair electrons and it results in the formation of an ion.&amp;nbsp;In the ordinary covalent combinations electrons are shared equally, ie both participants donate equal numbers of electrons, whereas in coordinate covalent combination electrons are donated by only one of the participants.The Nitrogen atom for instance has a lone pair of electrons. It shares this with a proton that is hydrogen ion H+ from an acid to produce the ammonium ions NH4+. In the formation of ammonium ion the proton ie hydrogen ion that combines with the ammonia molecule carries over its positive charge to give ammonium ion.&amp;nbsp;Let\\\'s look at this properly:The formation of ammonium ion involves two stages&amp;nbsp;Stage 1: The formation of ammonium gas&amp;nbsp;Nitrogen bonds with 3 hydrogen atoms to become stable. The nitrogen atom has 7 electrons, meaning it has 5 valence electrons, therefore,&amp;nbsp; it needs a total of 3 electrons to become stable. A hydrogen atom on the other hand needs to either gain an electron or loss an electron to become stable. In this case however, it gains an electron by bonding with nitrogen to become a stable ammonia gas.Note: the bond type is a trigonal bipyramidal and it bond angle is 120OStage 2: The formation of ammonium ionThe ammonia gas formed now combines with a proton that is hydrogen ion. The positive charge on the hydrogen ion is carried over to the ammonia gas to give the positively charged ammonium ion.&amp;nbsp;Note: the bond type is tetrahedral and its bond angle is 109.5O or 109O 28\\\'Properties of Covalent compounds1. They consist of molecules which do not form ions in solution.&amp;nbsp;2. Because they do not form ions they do not conduct electricity and so they are non - electrolytes.3. They have low melting and boiling points.VSEPRThe Valence shell electron pair repulsion theory, or VSEPR states that the shape of a molecule depends on the number of pairs of electrons in the valence shell of the central atom. Electrons are negatively charged particles and the neighboring electrons pairs with each other so that the molecule assumes new positions.&amp;nbsp;In summary we learnt that:Chemical combinations are of two types, the intermolecular bonds and the intramolecular bonds.The electrovalent bonds involve transfer of valence electrons from an electropositive element usually a metal, to an electronegative element usually a non - metal.The covalent bonds involve the sharing of electrons. It is divided into simple or ordinary covalent bonding and co-ordinate or dative covalent bonding.I urge you to solve these examples in your spare time.Draw the formation of the following compoundsMagnesium oxide (Mg2+O2-)Calcium fluoride (Ca2+F-)Draw the formation of the following compoundsHydrogen peroxide (H2O2)Hydroxonium ion (H3O+)Phosphoryl chloride (POCl3)Have a lovely day!', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', 'b243a432-34a2-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0);
