(14, 0, 11, 1, 57, 3, 'Chemical combinations II.', 'a5072b1f-3482-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', 'In the last lesson, we considered the strong bonds; today weâ€™ll be considering the weak bonds.Letâ€™s dive right in!METALLIC BONDINGMetallic bonding is the bonding that occurs in metals. The atoms of a metal are arranged in such a way that their positive charges and negative charges attract each other as shown here.&amp;nbsp;The presence of metallic bond accounts for the following properties:&amp;nbsp;Malleability that is the ability to beat into shapes.Sonorous nature that is the ability to produce sounds.High melting and boiling points.Ductility that is the ability to be drawn into wire.Magnetic property that is the ability to attract magnet.Electrical and thermal conductivity this is the presence of free electrons.Lustrous nature that is the ability to be polished to shine.High tensile strength.HYDROGEN BONDINGHydrogen bonding is types of dipole to dipole attraction between molecules in which hydrogen atom is bonded to a highly electronegative element such as nitrogen, oxygen or fluorine. Due to differences in electronegativity value, a dipole is induced with hydrogen atom having a partial positive charge while the other has a partial negative charge as seen here.The attraction between the negative charged atoms of a molecule to the positively charged hydrogen atom in another molecule of the same compound forms the hydrogen Bond.Consequences of hydrogen bondingMolecules having hydrogen bonds have high boiling points due to strong intermolecular forces.Molecules with hydrogen bonds are highly soluble in polar solvents such as water.Hydrogen bonding accounts for water resistance.Hydrogen bonding also helps fibers absorb water.Hydrogen bonding explains why water has a high surface tension. The attraction of water molecules on the surface of water makes it behave like an elastic skin that enables insects to walk on it.VAN DER WAAL FORCESThese forces exist between molecules of the same atoms of the same elements. It was discovered by a Dutch scientist called Johannes Vanderwaal. Van der Waals forces are very weak intermolecular forces that exist between molecules of the same atoms of the same element as a result of temporary internal shifts in the distribution of electrons within a molecule. In a molecule of hydrogen gas, as one hydrogen atom pulls electrons leaving a slightly negatively charged hydrogen atom, a temporary dipole is set up in the molecule. It is called temporary because it is short lived and does not last long. A dipole is a pair separated by opposite charges. This temporary dipole in a molecule of hydrogen induces a similar dipole to a nearby hydrogen molecule. There is an attraction between the two molecules due to opposite charges this attraction is called van der waal forces.&amp;nbsp;DIPOLE â€“ DIPOLE INTERACTIONThe dipole - dipole forces of interaction between the negative pole of one molecule and the positive pole of another molecule of an atom between neighboring covalent molecule is due to the differences in electronegativity values. Dipole - dipole interaction of forces occurs mostly in molecules of hydrogen and highly electronegative elements. Elements like HCl and acetone molecules. They are weaker than the polar covalent bonds.Important things to note about dipole â€“ dipole forces:1. Dipole - dipole forces occur between covalent bonds of polar molecules.2. Dipole - dipole forces involves dipoles.3. Dipole - dipole forces form permanent dipole compounds to temporary dipoles of Van Der waals forces.&amp;nbsp;In summary we learnt that:The weak bonds, which are the intramolecular bonds include the:Metallic bonds which occurs in metals.Hydrogen bonds in which hydrogen atoms bond with a highly electronegative element.Van der Waal forces that exist between molecules of the same atoms of the same elements.Dipole - dipole forces of interaction between the negative pole of one molecule and the positive pole of another molecule of an atom.Practice how to identify between these intramolecular forces.See you soon.', 'nil', 'page', '', 1, '', '8c6b49e7-34a4-11eb-b7ac-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2021-02-24 16:40:44', '', 0),
(15, 0, 4, 1, 53, 5, 'What to Produce?', 'e960a5fb-361d-11eb-8b83-52540049a927', 'PRODUCTION THEORY RECAP&amp;nbsp;Hello!I\\\'m very confident you enjoyed the videos on the theory of\r\nproduction from start to finish. I actually believe you enjoyed it. Remember\r\nthat at the start of the production theory that we specified three objectives\r\nthat we should achieve at the end of this lesson. We said that at the end of\r\nthis lesson we should be able to define production, mention the types of production\r\nwe have and explain them and we should be able to list the factors of\r\nproduction and their characteristics. And I have no doubts that you can do all\r\nthat now. So, let\\\'s just run through the things we have done so far. &amp;nbsp;We define Production as the creation of goods and services\r\nfor the satisfaction of human wants. Or the transformation of raw materials\r\ninto finished or semi-finished goods. Or the creation of utility, while utility\r\nis the satisfaction that we derive from the consumption of goods and services.&amp;nbsp;After that, we looked at the types of goods or the types of\r\nproducts, where we said we have basically two types of goods which are consumer\r\ngoods and producer or capital goods. We defined consumer goods as those that\r\ncan no longer undergo production processes, but are meant for immediate\r\nsatisfaction of human wants, while capital or producer goods are those goods\r\nthat are basically made for the help they will provide in producing other\r\ngoods. They are called producer goods because they are used by producers in\r\nproducing other goods and services. &amp;nbsp;From there, we looked at the types of production where we said\r\nthat production is basically classified into two types, direct and indirect\r\nproduction. And we said that direct production is a small scale production that\r\nis meant for family consumption, while indirect production is a large scale\r\nproduction of goods and services for sale. It\\\'s production for the sake of\r\nexchange. And we further said that this indirect production is divided into\r\nthree subdivisions namely, primary, secondary and tertiary production. There, we\r\nsaid that the primary aspect of production has to do with everything that\r\nconcerns bringing out raw materials from their natural forms. It includes all\r\nthe extraction activities - mining, extraction of crude oil etc. We looked at\r\nsecondary production that deals with the transformation of raw materials gotten\r\nat the primary level into finished and semi-finished goods and every other\r\nconstruction work. From there, we looked at tertiary production that has to do\r\nwith the distribution of goods and services to the final consumers and\r\nrendering of professional services.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&amp;nbsp;Thereafter, we looked at the factors of production and we\r\nsaid that we have four factors of production which are land, labour, capital\r\nand entrepreneurship, and we looked at each of them and their characteristics.\r\nRemember that I told you that the reward for land is rent, the reward for\r\nlabour is wages or salaries, the reward for capital is interest and the reward\r\nfor entrepreneurship is profit.\r\n\r\n&amp;nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, this is where we bring this topic, the theory of\r\nproduction to an end. I would implore you to look at the questions that are\r\nprovided that will assess your understanding of this particular lesson. Go\r\nthrough them, answer them critically and at the end of it, you will know how\r\nmuch you have understood this lesson. Thank you very much. We are still pushing\r\non because you\\\'re a loyal subscriber to what we do here. Thank you!', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cEiK2CalArg&amp;ab_channel=ACADASUITEEconomics', 'page', '', 1, '', 'af33d92d-361f-11eb-8b83-52540049a927', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', '1970-01-01 01:00:00', 0, 0, 0, '2020-12-04 10:58:47', '', 0),
