(17, 0, 4, 1, 53, 5, 'Introduction to Economics', 'e96134bf-361d-11eb-8b83-52540049a927', 'Welcome back!In the first video we watched, we introduced the subject\r\nmatter of economics and I told you that this video will be dedicated to the\r\ndefinition of economics as given by many renowned authors in economics, the\r\nscope of economics, the importance of economics as well as the methodology of\r\neconomics. Then in the next video, we shall be looking at the basic concepts of\r\neconomics. What is economics?Economics has been defined by different authors from their\r\ndifferent perspectives. A lot of definitions of economics have been given and\r\nwe are going to be exploring some of these definitions. According to Adam Smith who is regarded popularly among the\r\neconomists as the father of economics, he defined economics as an inquiry into\r\nthe nature and causes of wealth of nations. Alfred Marshall was also a renowned\r\neconomist. He defined economics as the study of mankind in the ordinary\r\nbusiness of life. According to John Stuart Mill, he defined economics as the\r\npractical science of production and distribution of wealth. All these\r\ndefinitions of economics are very interesting but overtime, there is a\r\nparticular definition that has been general accepted as the most comprehensive\r\ndefinition of economics all around the world. And thatâ€™s the definition given\r\nby professor lord Lionel Robbins who defined economics as the science that\r\nstudies human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means which\r\nhave alternative uses.First, from Robbins\\\' definition, we can identify some key\r\nconcepts. And one of the key concepts is that economics is a science. That is\r\nvery interesting to understand that economics is a science. For those of you\r\nwho might have appreciated some science subjects, you might have felt that\r\neconomics is not a science. But itâ€™s coming to you now from me that economics\r\nis a science. The question is â€œwhat kind of science is economics?â€&amp;nbsp; because we know that there are many types of\r\nsciences. Economics belongs to the group of science subjects called social\r\nsciences. Economics is a social science subject. Why is it a social science\r\nsubject? It is a social science subject because it studies human behavior. Any\r\nscience subject or any subject that studies human behavior is regarded as a\r\nsocial science. So, economics is regarded as a science because it is a subject\r\nthat uses scientific method to study human behaviours. You know the scientific\r\nmethod for those of you who might have come across it. Scientific method begins\r\nwith problem identification or definition, you come to literature review,\r\nstatement of hypotheses, testing of those hypotheses stated and so on and so\r\nforth. So, economics uses the same scientific method used by pure sciences to\r\ninvestigate economic matters in the society. We have other concepts in the\r\ndefinition of Lionel Robbins that are of much interest. There is a concept of\r\nscarcity in that definition because we have something like the \\&quot;scarce\r\nmeans\\&quot;. The scarce means there is telling us that the means of satisfying\r\nhuman wants are limited. They are scarce in nature. We have another\r\nconcept-ends. Ends in that definition stands for human wants and these human\r\nwants are said to be insatiable. They are said to be too numerous to be\r\nsatisfied with the available resources. Remember we pointed out that these\r\nresources are scarce. Then, the next in that definition is that these scarce\r\nresources have alternative uses. That is to say, since you canâ€™t satisfy all\r\nthe human wants, that means these available resources can be put into different\r\nuses. If you have a list of wants and the resources are not enough to satisfy\r\nall of them at the same time, it then means that you have to choose among those\r\nwants. You have to choose among them the ones youâ€™re going to satisfy first. So\r\nyou see that the definition is very comprehensive and all embracing. So, that\r\nis why it is generally adopted as the most comprehensive definition of\r\neconomics.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSo I encourage you to\r\nlearn other definitions but it is expected that in your examinations, you\r\nshould among other definitions, cite this particular one and when citing it,\r\ntry to point out these key points that he mentioned: Economics as a science i.e\r\na social science because it&amp;nbsp;studies human behavior. Then, it studies human behavior in\r\nits relationship between ends i.e human wants and the scarce means of\r\nsatisfying these wants talking about limited resources.\r\n\r\nSo the next we are going to look at is the scope of\r\neconomics. Economics is generally divided into 2 major branches namely macro\r\nand micro economics. So weâ€™re going to look at the scope of economics within\r\nthis range. Micro economics is that aspect of economics that concerns itself\r\nwith the study of individual economic agents. When I say economic agents, I\r\nmean agents like the household, firms or businesses and the government. These\r\nare the 3 major economic agents we have- the household, the firm and the\r\ngovernment. So what micro economics does is that it singles out each of these\r\neconomic agents to understand how they operate. It doesnâ€™t combine them\r\ntogether to study them. It studies them one after the other as individuals. So\r\nmicro economists can just go into production and decide to study a particular\r\nfirm and its productive activities. So when you talk about the branch of\r\neconomics that deals with the study of the economy in units, we talk about\r\nmicro economics.\r\n\r\nThen the opposite of it is macro economics. As we all know,\r\nthe word macro means large. So, this is the aspect of economics that studies\r\nthe economy as a whole. It combines the different economic units in aggregates\r\nand tries to study them. So, this branch of economics deals with aggregates\r\nlike unemployment, inflation, national income, and so on and so forth.&amp;nbsp; These are aspects of Economics that have to\r\ndo with the whole economy as it is. So economics covers both the micro aspect\r\nof the economy and the macro aspect of the economy. \r\n\r\nThen, we talk about the importance of economics. Economics\r\nis very important because it teaches us scientific ways, scientific principles\r\nthat will help us in the management of our limited resources in trying to\r\nsatisfy our unlimited wants. We have noted here that human wants are insatiable.\r\nThey are too numerous to be satisfied with the available resources. So since\r\nhuman wants are insatiable and resources are limited then there is a problem.\r\nThat problem is how to manage the limited resources in satisfying our unlimited\r\nwants. And that is what economics has come to solve. That problem is what\r\neconomics tries to solve. How do we manage what we have to satisfy our\r\nunlimited wants? So the very essence of economics as a discipline is that it\r\nteaches us scientifically proven ways of using our limited resources\r\nefficiently and effectively in trying to satisfy our unlimited wants. Without\r\nthe study of economics, man would be in a very serious problem trying to\r\nutilize the available resources in meeting his unlimited wants. So you can see\r\nthat economics is very important. Itâ€™s important to an individual, important to\r\na family, very important to firms and even to the government. There is no human\r\nbeing on the face of the earth that the study of economics is not important to\r\nbecause all of us are faced with the problem of scarcity of resources. \r\n\r\nNext we are going to\r\nlook at the methodology of the study of economics. What method do economists\r\napply in their investigations? Remember Iâ€™ve told you that Economics uses the\r\nsame scientific method that other sciences use. The methodology of the study of\r\neconomics is the scientific method, the same scientific method that other\r\nscience subjects use. But one thing about economics is that it does not have a\r\nparticular laboratory like other pure sciences like chemistry, physics and so\r\non and so forth. So economics has the entire society as its own laboratory. And\r\nfunny enough, while other sciences can study animals or non-living things and\r\nsubject them to a particular condition to achieve what they want to achieve, Economics\r\nstudies human beings that cannot be subjected to those scientific control\r\nmeasures. You can see that economists are studying a higher science. It is a\r\nhigher science because itâ€™s dealing with human beings which are higher animals\r\nthat you cannot easily control their behaviours. So when people are trying to\r\nintimidate you with the fact that they are studying science, you can tell them\r\nas well that you are a science student because the course you study or the\r\nsubject you study which is Economics equally uses the same scientific method\r\nthat they use in studying their own pure sciences. In fact, you are even on a\r\nhigher pedestal.&amp;nbsp; The reason is that you\r\nare studying a higher science. So from what we have said so far, we havestudies human behavior. Then, it studies human behavior in\r\nits relationship between ends i.e human wants and the scarce means of\r\nsatisfying these wants talking about limited resources.\r\n\r\nSo the next we are going to look at is the scope of\r\neconomics. Economics is generally divided into 2 major branches namely macro\r\nand micro economics. So weâ€™re going to look at the scope of economics within\r\nthis range. Micro economics is that aspect of economics that concerns itself\r\nwith the study of individual economic agents. When I say economic agents, I\r\nmean agents like the household, firms or businesses and the government. These\r\nare the 3 major economic agents we have- the h